Description: Use lstat() instead of faccessat() for g_local_file_query_exists
 The g_local_file_query_exists() function uses faccessat() with the AT_EACCESS
 flag, which checks the effective user's file accessibility rather than file
 existence. This causes g_file_query_exists() to return FALSE for files that
 exist but are not accessible by the effective user, breaking the file save
 dialog in applications like the 360 browser.
 .
 Fix by using g_lstat() instead of faccessat(), which properly checks file
 existence regardless of permissions, matching the behavior before GLib 2.84.
Author: Codex Agent <codex@deepin.org>
Origin: https://github.com/Zeno-sole/glib2.0
Last-Update: 2026-07-21

--- a/gio/glocalfile.c
+++ b/gio/glocalfile.c
@@ -1261,8 +1261,10 @@ g_local_file_query_info (GFile                *file,
   return info;
 }
 
-/* FIXME: faccessat() is available on FreeBSD but appears to not work correctly
- * here. This needs diagnosing; https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glib/-/issues/3495
+/* Use g_lstat() to check file existence rather than faccessat() which
+ * checks file accessibility (effective user permissions) and can
+ * incorrectly return "file not found" even when the file exists.
+ * See: https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glib/-/issues/3495
  *
  * On Android (bionic as of 2015-02-24), faccess() returns EINVAL if any flags are set,
  * so we have to use the fallback path. See
@@ -1274,8 +1276,9 @@ g_local_file_query_exists (GFile        *file,
                            GCancellable *cancellable)
 {
   GLocalFile *local = G_LOCAL_FILE (file);
+  struct stat st;
 
-  return faccessat (0, local->filename, F_OK, AT_EACCESS | AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW) == 0;
+  return g_lstat (local->filename, &st) == 0;
 }
 #endif
